  "opinion": "Stereotype threat in STEM isn't just a theoretical concept—it's something I've seen play out in my own life and the lives of my neighbors. Growing up in a household where one parent had a PhD and the other a master's degree, I was always encouraged to pursue education, but I also felt the weight of expectations that came with being a woman in a field where men dominate. When I started working at a local retail store, I'd often hear colleagues say things like, 'You're so smart, you'll do great in STEM,' but that comment sometimes felt like a double-edged sword—it made me anxious about whether I was living up to those expectations. Stereotype threat is when someone's performance is affected by the belief that they belong to a group that is stereotyped as performing poorly in a particular domain. In STEM, this often means women and people of color feeling stressed about being judged as 'not good enough' because of their identity. I think we absolutely should address it. For me, it starts with small, everyday actions: listening without judgment, celebrating others' successes, and creating safe spaces where people feel they can be their true selves without fear of failure. In my community, I've seen how a single conversation can shift the narrative—from 'I can't do this' to 'I'm trying, and that's enough.' It's not about fixing people; it's about fixing the systems that make them feel inadequate. As someone who's anxious and has spent time on social media, I know how easily negative stereotypes can spread. So, addressing stereotype threat isn't just a good idea—it's a necessity for building a more inclusive world where everyone has a chance to thrive.",
